 fascinating drafts with the writer’s family history reveals increasing preferential treatment of those with greater relatedness to him: kin altruism, i.e., nepotism. This pattern helps explain many of Tolstoy’s choices amongst plot variants he considered, as well as some of the curious devices he utilizes to get readers to share his biases, such as coincidences, notions of “fate,” and aversion to incest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aTolstoy, Leo, 1828-1910 - Criticism and interpretation. Tolstoy, Leo, 1828-1910 - Voina i Mir Characters. Families-History-Fiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aNapoleonic Wars.  aRussian literature.  aTolstoy.  aaesthetics.  aancestors.  aautobiographical fiction.  abiopoetics.  acharacter arcs.  aevolutionary psychology.  afamily.  ahistory.  aincest.  akin altruism.  aliterary Darwinism.  anepotism.  aprototypes.  arelationships.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068820708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU0 cprintz978164469408440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781644694091?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644694091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644694091/original  a978-3-11-068820-